<p><h1 style="text-align: center;">Higher Order Linear Regression</h1></p>

<p>The function that we will try to predict via regression will be a sin function affected by some noise. The function is defined as y = sin(2*pi*X) + 0.1 * N where X is 20 samples from the uniform distribution between 0 and 1 and N is 20 samples from the normal guassian distribution. The x and y values are then split evenly into 10 training and 10 testing datapoints. </p>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<div class=" highlight hl-python"><pre><span></span><span class="n">x</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">torch</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">Tensor</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">random</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">uniform</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">20</span><span class="p">))</span>
<span class="n">n</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">torch</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">Tensor</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">random</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">normal</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">20</span><span class="p">))</span>
<span class="n">y</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">torch</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">Tensor</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">sin</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">2</span><span class="o">*</span><span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">pi</span><span class="o">*</span><span class="n">x</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="o">+</span> <span class="mf">0.1</span><span class="o">*</span><span class="n">n</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="n">train_x</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">x</span><span class="p">[:</span><span class="mi">10</span><span class="p">]</span>

<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>We will look at the performance of four different models on the train and test datasets. All of the models will use Root Mean Square Error as the evalutation metric where RMSE = sqrt(sum((predicted - actual)^2)/N). All coefficients for the models are found through gradient descent. The method of gradient descent updates the value of the weights based on the derivative of the loss function with respect to the weight. That is W_new = W_old - 0.01*dL/dW, where the constant 0.01 is the learning rate dictating the impact of the gradient on the new weight. This method of gradient descent is applied for each and every weight, w, of the model. The four models to be tested are of zeroth, first, third, and ninth order regression. The definitions for the models can be found below, beginning with the zeroth order model.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>

  <span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">__init__</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="bp">self</span><span class="p">):</span>

  <span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">forward</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="bp">self</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">x</span><span class="p">):</span>
    <span class="k">return</span> <span class="bp">self</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">w0</span>
  
  <span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">loss</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="bp">self</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">x</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">y</span><span class="p">):</span>
    <span class="n">y_pred</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="bp">self</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">forward</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">x</span><span class="p">)</span>
    <span class="k">return</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="n">y_pred</span> <span class="o">-</span> <span class="n">y</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="o">*</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="n">y_pred</span> <span class="o">-</span> <span class="n">y</span><span class="p">)</span>

  <span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">train</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="bp">self</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">epochs</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">train_x</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">train_y</span><span class="p">):</span>
    <span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">epoch</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="nb">range</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">epochs</span><span class="p">):</span>
      <span class="bp">self</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">total_loss</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">0</span>
      <span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">x_val</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">y_val</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="nb">zip</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">train_x</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">train_y</span><span class="p">):</span>

        <span class="bp">self</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">total_loss</span> <span class="o">+=</span> <span class="n">l</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">data</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">numpy</span><span class="p">()</span>
        <span class="n">l</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">backward</span><span class="p">()</span>

        <span class="bp">self</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">w0</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">data</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="bp">self</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">w0</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">data</span> <span class="o">-</span> <span class="mf">0.01</span><span class="o">*</span><span class="bp">self</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">w0</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">grad</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">data</span>
        <span class="bp">self</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">w0</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">grad</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">data</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">zero_</span><span class="p">()</span>
      <span class="bp">self</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">total_loss</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">sqrt</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="bp">self</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">total_loss</span><span class="o">/</span><span class="nb">len</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">train_x</span><span class="p">))</span>

<p>Analysis of the graphs shows that the zeroth and first order models are prone to underfitting. Underfitting is the phenomenon that occurs when a model is not complex enough to actually model the true function. The third and fourth order models have signs of overfitting seen from the graphs above. Overfitting is the opposite of underfitting, where a model is too complex for the data being modeled and thus additional artifacts such as noise may end up affecting the prediction more than the true function. In the ninth order graph above it can be seen that the function perfectly passes through some of the training points but fails to predict the arcs of the sin function as the model is overfit to specific samples. </p> <p>After visualizing the models on training dataset we then test the prediction capabilities of the models on the test dataset. The same RMSE metric is used for performance evaluation so that we can compare train and test loss accurately. An example for testing the zeroth order model is shown below.</p>

<p>It can be seen in the graph above that the model takes on a form much more similar to the sin function than previously with less data points. </p> <p>Another method that can be used to combat overfitting is regularization. Regularization is the method of adding some magnitude of the weights to the loss function in order to penalize larger weights as these are typically the result of overfitting. For the following experiments we will use L2 regularization where the weights are squared for penalization. The loss function will be of the form shown below. </p>

<p>It can be seen above that the model performs best with smaller values of lambda. This is because the model is not overfitting too much to begin with and the small value of lambda helps limit the minimal amount of overfitting of the model. As lambda grows larger the error increases due to the models inability to increase the weights as they attribute to the error too much. This results in more underfitting as the weights are no longer able to grow and become locked into a much smaller domain. </p> <p>In conclusion we see that the best performing model for both the train and test samples is the ninth order model with L2 regularization and lambda = 1/100000 with a train loss of .24 and a test loss of .307 </p>
